{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_jam_ver01/data/sn83025020/00202191186/1907100901/0630.xml":{"full_text":"1 1\n\"V\" \"TT\" t. y\nVIM\nA\nP A II\npi -jny jr it i -7 in rq a ir iT\nVOL. IX No. 2S4\nV1NITA, OKLAHOMA,' WEDNESDAY, OCTOliEli i:\nFIVK CENTS r K R COPY\ny\n-t-aja-wx--c-...--x.uv.a---jr .r, .cannula Jrsvrwfccij. u.\nSale\n\"A\nI\nof\nBlankets\nAND\nComforts\nHaving bought my stook of comforts and blankets before the\nadvance in cotton goods, I will sell at special prices during the\nmonth oi October as follows:\nSI M1SSSAPP DIE\nSamuel F. Whitlow of Iloran Says\nthe Girl Killed Herself Because\nof Infatuation for Him.\n50c Blankets ..43c\n75c Blankets...... Sc\n$1.25 Blankets 98c\n1.75 Blankets $1.32\n$1.25 Comforts 98c\n51.65 Comforts $1.32\n$2.00 Comforts .$l,67\n$2.50 Comforts.... $1J)8\nand up to $3.50\natsen's\nCOIiGJO VIN1TA\nSplendid Opportunities Awaiting at\nOur Door To Be Admitted.\nIf the proper efforts are set forth\nVinita mav secure a large class fac\ntory in the near future1 City Clerk\nGeo. P. P'ogee has been in communl\ncation with Shaler Bros, of Muncie,\nInd the largest manufacturers of\nglass in the United States They\nmade inauiries regarding the cost of\ngas, building- site, railroad facilities,\netc.. and expressed a desire to locate\nhere if they can get any inducements\nt A factory of this nature would employ\nfrom three to four hundred men, most\nlit whom would become prominent\ncit'zens of our town. i.is is one of\nmany institutions that require an\nenormous outlay of money for help\nand other Inadequate expense. This\nis a matter that should attract the\nattention of our business men and\nsteps should be taken at once to look\ninto the matter.\nMr. Fogle has also received inquiries\nfrom C. M. Welch at Nicholson, Kan.,\nregarding the building of a hemp fac\ntory at this place. He is desirous of\ngetting the people here interested in\nplanting hemp and proposes himself,\nto rent several thousand acres that he\nmay cultivate himself, using steam\nplows to cultivate same. lie asks no\nbonds but prefers to have seme man\nof capital to start himself in the n\nterprise. He has a patent hemp brake\nthat requires about one-half the time\nin putting the material on the mark\net. C. N. Yokum, of San Francisco,Cal.\nwrites here to ascertain the outlook\nfor a big department store at this\nplace, and other Inquiries are coming\nfrom many sources regarding the fu\nture of Vinita and business outlook.\nAil of these matters are of vital im\nportance to Vinita. This is a new\ncountry, factories are seeking suitable\nlocations where they can be operated\ncheapest and meet our splendid facili\nties and natural resources. We can\noffer to manufacturing industries ev\nery inducement that is desired. With\nthese factories, Vinita 's future' is as\nsured.\nCOUHTT COMMISSIONERS\nDISCUSS CONDITIONS\nA. A. Barker, \"Democratic Commis\nsioner elect, of Kennsaw was here\nyesterday. The purpose of his visit\nhere was to confer with the other\nmembers of the board in regard to\nthe condition the county will be\nplaced in when the president issues\nhis statehood proclamation.. It is the\nintention of the board to make pro\nvision for the caring of the prisoners\nof Craig County and providing a place\nof holding the district and county\ncourts and offices for the several coun\nty officers. The board at this time\nhas no power to make any contracts\nfor the county but they purpose to be\nready to promptly take care of this\nurirent business of the county Im\nmediately after the Statehood pro\nclamation is issued.\n(f\n3S\n11 lit\nTTi A TT\nA\nEmpire Block\nDon't rest until you have seen\nour line of MILLINERY We\nlead on low prices\nSee our pretty line of Pictures and Frames\n5c up to $5.00\nBig bargains in Towels, Tabic Linen\nFlannels and Ginghams\nIola, Kas., Oc-t. 9 A strral i )i,al\ndevelopment came joshed xy in the\nmysterious death of Mi; s :y Fapp,\nthe daughter of John X. Sir-- of Mo\nral), wlio wjs foucd dead In the back\nyard of hdr fathei's home with her\nthroat cut. It was learned Tuesday\nmorning that after being under in\nvestigation practically every since the\ntragedy Samuel F. Whitlow, a grain\nand coal dealer of Moran, who form\nerly was a teacher to whom Miss Sapp\nhad gone to school, had confessed last\nMonday night that he was at her\nside when the razor was drawn across\ntne throat or tne yong woman.\nIt was suicide, is the assertion of\nWhitlow. He says she killed herself\nfor love of him and because he would\nnot desert his family and go away\nwith her. The father and brother-iu-\nlaw of the girl declare ir was not sui\ncide. Whitlow is under aires'!. Whit\nlow attempted suicide on the way from\nMorr.n to Iola Monday night.\nnow THE CLEW WAS FOUND.\nThe county attorney believes that\nthe new developments in the case are\nof great Importance and gives much\ncredit to the Plnkerton detective who\nhad worked on the case only since a\nweek ago Tuesday. Last Monday\nmany people, among them some of\nthe county officers who had been\nworking on the case for three days,\nsaid the mystery of the girl's death\nwould never be cleared.\nAt that time several stories of\nWhitlow's peculiar actions the night\nof the tragedy had reached the au-\nthorftis' ears. The detectives sifted\nall these stories idovrn and learned\nthat there was a wide variance In\nsome of Whitlow's statements con\ncerning details of his actions thenight\nMiss Sapp was found dead in the back\nyard of her home.\nii was wwie tne coroner s jury was\nin seslou that Whitlow admitted to\nthePinkerton detective that Jie knew\nall about the girl's death. The coron\ners Jury was huredly adjourned un\ntil yesterday and preparations made\nto let Whitlow tell all his storv\nto the county j officers. He made\nhis statement late Tuesday night.\nNil ti oi\nXJ\n1 1 y y .f\"f'\n'A vv vtJi\ntt\nJ\nFrom tooda\nPiece Goods.\nMade to Ycur Measure\nselected from our larfje stock of\nill I wM jLiiiiiitiitt.i 'Min i- i nti-i j\n375 si\"\nPrice for malting\n!:$4.00,\nPrice for making\n54.00 sli\ni m. a y s 1\n8 i:HI\nPrice for making\n$4.05\nForty-eig'ht different styles to se\nledl fromr Workmanship the best.\nFit and satisfaction guaranteed.\nSuits, Palmer garment, made to\nyour order, $30 up.\nYour choice of dozens of popular fabrics.\nSELBY\nSHOES\n$2.50 to\n$6.00\nJ7 rrt\nQUEEN\nQuality\nShoes\n$3 00 to\n$4 00\ni 1T1CL\nDepartment of the Interior, Com\nmissioner to the Five Civil\nized Tribes.\nVisit Our Millinery Department\n3 Roils Cotton for\n3 Gas Mantels for\n25c\n25c\n3 PairsLadies orAIen's Hose 26c\nLow Prices on Dishes\nNotice is hereby given that from\nOctober 10th to October 12th, in\nclusive, the outstanding tickets of\nadmission will be received at the\nCherokee land office on the dates\nnamed. Holders of such tickets\nshould apply only on the dates indi\ncated to avoid unnecessary expense\nand delay, as chey will be admitted\nonly on thejjdates designated unless\nany ticket cannot be reached, in\nwhich event such ones will be admit\nted first on the following day:\nThursday, October 10, 4651 to 4800,\ninclusive.\nFriday, October 11, 4801 to 4950,\ninclusive.\nSaturday, October 12, 4051 to 5050,\ninclusive.\nMonday, October 14, 5,051 to5,lo0\ninclusive.\nTuesday, October 15, 5,101 to 5,150\ninclusive.\nWednesday, October 16, 6151 to 5200\ninclusive.\nThursday, October 17, 5,201 to 5,250\ninclusive.\nFriday, October 18, 5,251 to 5,300\ninclusive.\nSaturday, October 19, 5,301 to 5,350\ninclusive.\nMonday, October 21, 5,351 to 5,400\ninclusive.\nTuesday, October 22, 5,401 to 5,450\ninclusive.\nWednesday, October 23, 5,451 to 5,rC0\nInclusive.\nThursday, October 24, 5,501 to 5,50\nInclusive.\nFriday, October 25, 5,551 to 5.6C0\ninclusive.\nW. C. Pollock,\nActing Commissioner.\nDated at Muskogee, I. T.,\nOct. 7, 1907.\n'A HID DEAD\nIndications Are That He Fell Out of\na Tree With Fatal Results\nWarm When Found\nSapulpa, I. T., Oct. 8 Late last ev\nening, the authorities in the city\nwere notided that a dead man had\nbeen found in a field near Pole Cat\nbridge, and accordingly, officer Dick\nHarper and a numner of others went\nout to investigate. Onarrivingatthe\ndesignated place they found the body\nof a middle aged man, which was still\nwarm, indicating that he had died but\na short time before.\nWhen the officer and others arrived\nthey found the body lying face down,\nwiih a slight abrasion back of the left\near, and his ngnt jeir broken in two\nplaces, and from all appearances he\nhad climbed up In a tree and had fal\nlen out, with the results above stated\nThe name on the letters indicated\nthat the man's name is A.M. LaPlant.\nHis trunk has been at the depot since\nSeptember 30, and there are some\nstorage charges on it. II13 pocket\nbook.contafoed trunk keys, papers, to\nbacco tags, trunk check and a bill of\ngoods bought at Caney, Kans., Sept.\n24, 1907.\nTwo HIttoric Cabarets.\nTwo old Sevres cabarets, each with\nan interesting history of its own, will\nbe Included in the porcelain sale et\nChristie's, eays a writer in the Pall\nMall Cazette. The first, painted with\nfestoons of flowers, was formerly the\nproperty of Marie Antoinette, and was\ngiven by Louise Lefevre, her valet de\npied, to George Earl of Essex, and by\nhim to Miss Fannie Kelly, the actress,\nin 1818, from whom it descended to\nthe present owner, who is Miss Kel\nly's adopted daughter. The second,\npainted with musical and amatory tro\nphies, was presented by George IV\nwhen Prince of Wales to Mrs. Rob\ninson, the celebrated actress, and at\nthe sale of her husband's effects was\npurchased by John Graham, in the\nsame sale will be found a Chippendale\nmahogany bookcase, exquisitely carv\ned, which was formerly at the Kensing\nton palace, in the room lu which\nGeorge II. died.\nVOUVE N. rUHHS\nroaiMLii. vmhopY.\nI COMING'!\n1. Nine lm t I\nihiikA J\nv..\n3 nr.:.T\nAdvertisers will bear in mind that\nthe circulation of the Daily Chieftain\nexceeds 700 and that it is admitted to\ntratismission through the U. S. Mails\nas a daily newspaper. Remember\nfurther that its pay roll exceeds that\nof any other institution employing the\nsame amount of help in Vinita all of\nwhich is jpent here, and that's what\nmakes a town.\nMrs. Mitchell went to Muskogee last\nuight to attend the examining board\nof Pharmacy. He was accompanied\nby his sister Miss Eodo, of Seneca.\nA cattleman over In Western Okla\nhoma has been sued for $10,000 by a\nmilliner. The facts in the case re\nabout as follows: The cattleman\nwanted to sell a friend. The new mil\nliner had just come to town and open\ned a millinery business. The cattle\nman thought he saw his opportunity\nby pretending to know the; new mil\nliner stating that she had just gotten\nout of jail. What was she in jail for'?\ninquired the friend. \"Sticking a hat\npin through a sailor,\" replied the cat\ntleman. The news got out over town\nthr.t the new milliner had just got out\nof j4 and caused- her much annoy\nance and she brought suit for di mag\nes in the sum of f IO.C00. f\nClinched.\nThe Insurance agent had exhausted\nhis arts. With tears welling from his\neyes and in a voice quivering with\nemotion he had recitetd the harrow\ning tale of widow and orphans in dire\ndistress through the untimely death of\ntheir taoughtless protector. But the\nfarmer was unmoved. \"Nope, I\nguess I'll not take any to-day,\" he\naid, and reached for his red ban\ndanna. \"But,\" said the wily agent,\n\"with every policy goes an almanac,\na plug of Greenville, a brass watch, an\naccordeon and a bottle of liver medi\ncine, besides a brass band to head\nyour funeral procession. \"Gosh ding!\"\ncame the reply. \"Give me one. No\nbody can ever say Joshua Hay\nneglected the welfare of his loved\na singular forest or stone columns\nat Dikilatch, In Bavaria, has been vis\nited by Prof. De Launay, a French\ngeographer, who reports that this ruin-\nhke formation extends over a SDace\nabout 1,500 feet long by 100 to 150\nfeet broad, on the edge of a plateau\nla the open country, the columns be\ning 15 to 20 feet high, and some of\nthem a yard thick, their share being\nabsolutely cylindrical. They bave\nbeen produced by erosion of masses\nof the gray nunimulitic limestone,\nbroken by joining. A special study\nwas made by Prof. De Launay, and he\nconcludes that whirls in the bed of\ntorrent gave the column their Isoia-\nAT VINITA, MONDAY,\nOCTOBER\n14\nj va f.s:;ss\n2 PEMSERIES\n3 mm\n3 REGAL EQl'IXE FAS.1S\n\"iC'O Pecple, Ksrses zr.i Hire Aniir.afs.\nl.V World's Most Boted and Daring Male\nFemale aad Brute Periormcrs\nSP&NINB DEATH'S ASCII AWKEEl\nBy A CHAKMIKG TOtJHS LADY.\nrt j Higl.esi Priced, Most Thrilllnt) Free\n():tt-Uaor Attraction rvsr known.\nn Audacious, Reckless, Fool-Hardy Frenc, Boauty\n6HE FURTS TWICE DAILY WITH DEATH.\ni\nmmtdlst' atfff Paradm nod g'n M -10 P. M.\nBUT ONE OF THE COUNTLESS FASCINATING\nSipcr-Ssnsjllcsil, EXCLUSIVE FEATURES.\nGiving you more than you ever befor got or v\ndreamed of getting.\nWonderful Equestr'nn?, Aeria'.ists, Gymnasts an?\nAcroba'i. Karvelous Leaper1,, Tumblers and\nB;cych5ta, Famous Artists and\nREALLY FUNNY CLOWNS 41\nEDUCATED ELEPHANTS. POMES. DOGS\nAND OTHER VALUABLE ANIMALS.\nOUR TRIPLE MENAGERIES\nSimpf'si! tne la-rest Zoo Eitar-t and confaJns t'i\nOnly Wliij b acK Crt-f'-i ev-r ex-, i t.-, r v.\nk'i the Globe's sttani;st, most ci:' cus (.t.e:mjns o\nAmrr.al Li!i from Eartn, Air and Ssa,\ntion and sha;e.\nCOME TO TOWN t&RLY AVO W'TSE PS THE\nGlOf'IOUS, MAjESTIC, tiR.LLIANT,\nll-LUSTRIOl'S, IMPOSlNw, GA)t\nPARADE\nJlT 10 A. M. R&iN CR SHINE.\n3- r r t -t r m a x c 1 s o a 1 i.v- a\nAl i and 8 p. m., Coorl op?n 1 and 7 p.m.\nFREE\nC i\" ip k","height":"27092","width":"17956"}}
